Now suppose that X is arbitrary, but non-singular. By the duality theorem for \mathbf {P}, we have an isomorphism \operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathscr {F}) = \operatorname {H}^n(\mathbf {P},\mathscr {F})' = \operatorname {Ext}_{\mathcal {O}_\mathbf {P}}^{r-n}(\mathbf {P};\mathscr {F},\Omega _\mathbf {P}^r). By , the far-right-hand side can be identified with \operatorname {Hom}_{\mathcal {O}_\mathbf {P}}(\mathbf {P};\mathscr {F},\omega _X^n) = \operatorname {Hom}_{\mathcal {O}_X}(X;\mathscr {F},\Omega _X^n) = \operatorname {Ext}_{\mathcal {O}_X}^0(X;\mathscr {F},\Omega _X^n) whence we have an isomorphism
